âœ… Step-by-Step Fix (Use Windows-style path):
ðŸ‘‰ Step 1: Create the .ssh directory manually
Run this command in PowerShell:
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh

This will create:
C:\Users\khyat_jerv3vv\.ssh

ðŸ‘‰ Step 2: Generate SSH key and save it in the correct folder
Now run:
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048 -f $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\my-local-key

                   or
In your terminal (Linux/Mac/WSL):
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048 -f "C:\Users\khyat_jerv3vv\.ssh\my-local-key"




âœ… Step 4: Connect to Bastion via EC2 Instance Connect
Go to the EC2 Console

Select the Public EC2 (Bastion) â†’ Click Connect

Use EC2 Instance Connect
Once inside, run:
mkdir -p ~/.ssh
nano ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

Copy the full public key from local and paste it into nano, save with:
Set permissions:
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
This ensures:

.ssh folder is only accessible to you
authorized_keys has strict read/write access


âœ… Step 3: (Optional) Verify Key Access Works
From your cli , try:
